<h2 id="ideal">15. What Makes an Ideal Profile (Track A, Tier 1)</h2>
<ul>
  <li>100,000+ followers (Mid-Tier or Macro) → D5 ≥ 80</li>
  <li>Verified account (blue tick) → D4 +30</li>
  <li>High follower/following ratio (≥ 10x) → D4 +22</li>
  <li>"DM open", email in bio, or explicit partnership language → D2 = 82–100</li>
  <li>Bio mentions building AI/voice apps, LLM tools, or voice AI specifically → D3 ≥ 90</li>
  <li>Regular poster with AI content → more search hits</li>
</ul>

<div class="box-green">
  <strong>Perfect Tier 1 example:</strong> @karpathy — 1M+ followers (D5=95), verified (D4+30), ratio ≥15x (D4+35), well-known AI educator (D3=90+), occasionally mentions partnerships → Overall ~87. Tier 1, Track A.
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="dedup">16. Deduplication — No Account Appears Twice</h2>
<h3>Layer 1 — seenThisRun Set (in-memory, per run)</h3>
<p>Every handle is added to a JavaScript Set the moment it appears in any search result. If the same handle appears again in a different keyword search (e.g. @vapidev matched both "voice ai" AND "vapi developer"), the second occurrence is silently skipped. This means each profile is only fetched once per run, saving API calls.</p>

<h3>Layer 2 — DB UNIQUE constraint (permanent, across runs)</h3>
<p>The <code>handle</code> column in the <code>accounts</code> table has a UNIQUE constraint. Every write is an UPSERT:</p>
<pre>If handle already exists in DB → UPDATE (refresh scores with latest data)
If handle is new              → INSERT (add new row)</pre>
<p>This means running the agent multiple times never creates duplicate records. It only refreshes scores.</p>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="dbwrite">17. Database Write — What Gets Saved</h2>
<p>Database: Turso (libSQL — SQLite running on edge infrastructure).</p>
